        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_23130_1819_07_20_page01.jpg"/>
                <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
                <opener>
                    <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                        <date when="1819-07-20"/>20 July 1819</dateline>
                    <salute>
                        <persName>
                            Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss Edgeworth</persName><lb/><!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                        </persName>
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p> When this shall happen to reach your hands<lb/>
                    it will be accompanied by a second edition of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1">Walter<lb/>
                        Scott</persName> a <hi rend="underline">tall</hi> copy as collectors say and bound in Turkey<lb/>
                    leather garnished with all sorts of fur and frippery - not<lb/>
                    quite so well lettered <del></del> however as the old and <unclear>unverified</unclear><lb/>
                    <del></del> of the original <add>edition</add>. in <unclear>other</unclear>&amp; &amp; <unclear>more</unclear>] intelligible<lb/>
                    phrase the tall cornet of Hussars whom this will introduce<lb/>
                    to you is my eldest son who is now just leaving me to<lb/>
                    join his regiment in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>. I have charged him &amp; he is is<lb/>
                    himself sufficiently anxious to <unclear>omit</unclear> no opportunity of<lb/>
                    making your acquaintance as to be known to the good<lb/>
                    and the wise is by far the best privilege he will derive<lb/>
                    from my connection with literature. I have always felt<lb/>
                    the value of having access to persons of talent and genius<lb/>
                    to be the best part of a literary mans prerogative and<lb/>
                    you will not wonder I am sure that I should be <choice><orig>desi-<lb/>
                        rous</orig><reg>desirous</reg></choice> this youngster should have a share of the same<lb/>
                    benefit.<lb/></p>
                <p> I have had dreadful bad health for many months<lb/>
                    <unclear>passed</unclear> and have endured more pain than I thought<lb/>
                    was <unclear>consistent</unclear> with life. But the thread though frail in<lb/>
                    some respects is tough in others and here am I with<lb/>
                    renewed health and a fair prospect of regaining my<lb/>
                    strength the much exhausted by such a train of suffering<lb/></p>
                  <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_23130_1819_07_20_page02.jpg"/>  
                 <p> I do not know when this will reach you my<lb/>
                    <del></del> sons motions being uncertain But find you where<lb/>
                     or when it will it comes <del>for</del> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Dear Miss Edgeworth</persName> from<lb/>
                    the sincere admirer of your genius and of the patriotic<lb/>
                    and excellent manner in which it has always been<lb/>
                    exerted In which character I subscribe myself<lb/></p>
                
                <p>  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotW1"><hi rend="underline">Walter Scott</hi></persName><lb/></p>
                  
                <p><placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Abbotsford-House_STK">Abbotsford Melrose</placeName><lb/>
                    20 July 1819<lb/></p>
                <closer>
                    <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p><!--A postscript goes here, outside the <closer>. --></p>
                </postscript>
                <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
                <!-- Format for postscripts. 
               Postscripts do NOT go inside closer tags. Adjust to take into account the order in your letter. 
               Sometimes the signature is on page three, the address on page four, then the postscript follows back on the top of page one, for example.-->
